\cs15\fs16\up6 K} unsolicited;serial;errors}}{\fs20\ulnone Unsolicited Serial Port Data Received}{\f9\fs20\ulnone 
\par }\pard\plain \fs20 {\f9 
\par The application presents this error message when unexpected data is being received via the serial port.  This may indicate that the device is in a test or diagnostic mode.  If such a condition occurs and consistently interferes with reading or writing dat
a to or from the device, first try resetting the device via the }{\f9\uldb reset}{\v\f9\cf13 HID_PAGER_SW_RESET} {\f9 menu option.  
\par 
\par It may be necessary to manually reset the device by removing the battery, inserting the battery with the poles reversed, then removing the battery again and re-inserting it with the poles in the original position.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\sb240 \b\f2\ul \page {\cs15\f0\fs20\ulnone\up6\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \fs20 {\cs15\fs16\up6 $} Serial Port Error}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \fs20 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} HIDP_SERIAL_PORT_ERROR}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \fs20 {
\cs15\fs16\up6 K} serial;port;error}}{\fs20\ulnone Serial Port Error}{\f9\fs20\ulnone 
\par }\pard\plain \fs20 {\f9 
\par Generally, serial communications errors result from system configuration conflicts or interface connection failures.  Since connection failures are the most common and easily resolved, use the following check
-list to ensure the device is connected properly:
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s49 \f9\fs20 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab 
If the device is connected via a programming fixture, ensure that the fixture is powered properly.  If the universal pager programming fixture adapter is in use (i.e. RIB box), the red LED should appear on if the device is properly seated in the fixture.

\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab The RS232 cable must be a straight-thru connection.  Null-Modem type cables will not work.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab 
If the application indicates that the device did not respond, ensure that the cable is connected to the RS232 connector on the PC as well as to the programming fixture.  If the device is connected by a 3-pin cable, ensure the device-end of the cable is fi
rmly attached to the device.  Additionally, if a programming fixture is in use, ensure that the device is seated in the fixture properly and that the connection prongs are not catching on the device casing.  Also try causing a \ldblquote break\rdblquote 
 on the line by removing the device from the fixture and re-inserting it.  Then, re-attempt the failed operation.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If you cannot determine which port number the device is physically attached to, use the {\uldb Serial Port}{\v\cf13 HID_PAGER_COMMO} menu to select another port.  Try each available port in-turn in order to find the device.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If the device is displaying a low-battery indicator, replace the battery.  It may be necessary to turn the device off for a period of time to allow the internal battery to re-charge.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If the device does not respond to key-presses, manually reset the device by reversing the battery and then reversing it again to the original position. 
\par 
\par 
\par System conflicts occur due to improper configurations among the application, the serial port driver, the system IRQ settings, and the serial port UART.  Use the following checklist to resolve system conflicts:
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab The serial port is initially configured to utilize a specific base address and interrupt request line (IRQ)
.  This configuration is loaded only once upon Windows start-up.  It is possible for the configuration to become corrupted.  Usually, corruption occurs when a serial communications based application (typically DOS based) accesses the serial port without u
tilizing the driver supplied with Windows.  If corruption occurs, all other Windows serial communications based applications will be unable to utilize the serial port(s).  The only way to reset the port configuration is to exit and re-start Windows.  

\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Ensure that the Serial Port Settings under the Program Manager Control Panel icon are correct for use with the application.  The settings are baud rate of 9600, 8 data bits, 1 stop bit, no parity. 
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If the application indicates that a \ldblquote system timer\rdblquote  associated error occured, exit other applications in order to free system resources for use with this application.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If communication errors occur erratically or immediately after installing the application, an IRQ conflict may be present on the system, refer to the file \ldblquote win31com.txt\rdblquote 
 located in the directory in which the application has been installed.  The file contains detailed information on the analysis and resolution of system conflicts.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240 \b\f2\ul \page {\cs15\f9\fs20\ulnone\up6\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \fs20 {\cs15\fs16\up6 $} Custom Default Configuration}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \fs20 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} hs_default_configuration}}{\f9\fs20\ulnone 
