\cs15\fs16\up6 K} GPIB;MDA;tuning}}{\f9\fs20\ulnone MDA/GPIB Operation
\par }\pard\plain \fs20 {\f9 
\par The application is designed to utilize an HP 53310A Modulation Domain Analyzer (MDA) connected to the PC via a GPIB card.  When the Auto-Tune button is pressed on the Tuning Dialog window, the application will attempt to tune the device using measurements
 obtained via the MDA.  Use the following information to diagnose Auto-Tune related failures. 
\par 
\par If a }{\b\f9 GPIB}{\f9  specific error message is presented, note the following:
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s49 \f9\fs20 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab 
The application utilizes the GPIB routines included with the National Instruments Corporation NI-488.2M gpib.lib for Windows 3.0/3.1.  If your GPIB card is not compatible with this library, then the GPIB specific functionality of the appl
ication will not work.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab The application assumes the GPIB card is configured as GPIB0.  If
 your GPIB card is not configured as such, edit the application initialization file (pps.ini located in the Windows directory) and either append or modify the following entry.  Then, save the file and re-launch the application.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab [GpibSettings]
\par \tab \tab \tab CardAddress=0
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab The application searches the GPIB bus for the HP 53310A Modulation Domain Analyzer.  If the device is not found, first ensure that an MDA is actually attached to the GPIB0 bus.  Then, ensure that the MDA is configured as {\b 
Addressed} via the {\b Utility : HP-IB/PRINT}
 MDA menu.  After the MDA is initially found, the MDA GPIB address is recorded in the pps.ini file (located in the Windows directory).  Subsequent application sessions will first attempt to find the MDA at that location.  If the MDA does not respond at th
e recorded address, then the application will conduct a full search.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Consult your GPIB User\rquote s manual for more descriptive explanations of the GPIB error and status codes. 
\par 
\par 
\par If an {\b Automated Tuning} or {\b MDA} specific error message is indicated, note the following:
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab 
Only automated tuning of the Modulation Balance and Symbol Deviation parameters is supported.  It is assumed that the Reference Oscillator has already been tuned.  Verify reference oscillator tuning prior to initiating automated modulatio
n balance tuning.  Symbol deviation tuning should be performed last.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab It is imperative that the device have a well-charged NiCad battery in order to effectively accomplish automated tuning.  It may be necessary to allow the NiCad to charge prior to attempting automated tuning. 
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If an error message indicating {\b measurement out of specification}
 appears, the measured signal is of such poor quality that continued automated tuning would probably not be effective.  It may be beneficial to ensure that the device NiCad battery is well charged.  Additionally, if the displayed tuning configuration para
meters are far away from their default settings, try using the defaults and re-attempt automated tuning. 
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If the signal appears significantly offset from the expected center frequency, ensure that Reference Oscillator Tuning has been accomplished.   
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab If an error message indicating {\b tuning parameters modified} appears, the results of tuning have been recorded and are visible in the Tuning Dialog window parameter configuration section.  The values may be acceptable e
ven though the tuning operation halted.  This may occur if successive auto-tune operations have depleted the device NiCad to the point that further tuning will result in questionable results.  If the values are not acceptable, press the Undo button to ret
rieve the original configuration.  You may have to wait until the NiCad recharges to test the tuned parameters for acceptability.
\par 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab The application does not configure the MDA for use with an external reference local oscillator (LO).  If an L
O is in use with the MDA, ensure that the reference frequency is set properly relative to the configured tuning center frequency (as displayed on the application\rquote 
s tuning dialog, configuration section).  Use the corresponding suggested LO Frequency as displayed via the MDA {\b Utility : LO MENU}
 menu.  For example, if the tuning center frequency is 901.40625 Mhz, then the signal generator should be set to provide a reference frequency of 894.0 Mhz to the MDA.  The MDA and signal generator will need to be manuall
y configured for external LO usage.
